I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the API data, as this is the first step in the workflow.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now that we've successfully fetched the API data, I'll proceed with the next step which is to validate and parse the data. I'll use the data_processing_parser tool for this purpose.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since the error indicates the parser expects XML format but we're working with JSON data (from the API fetch), I'll modify the options parameter to specify the input format explicitly. I'll retry the data_processing_parser with the correct format specification.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "options": {
    "input_format": "json"
  }
}
</tool_call>

            I'll try using the data_processing_transformer tool instead, as it's specifically designed for format conversion and might better handle the JSON data from the API. I'll specify both input and output formats as JSON.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now that we've successfully transformed the data, I'll proceed with validating it against a schema using the data_processing_validator tool. Since no specific schema was provided, I'll use a default validation schema.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array"
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>
